    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Property and Equipment Disclosures in Amazon\'s 2025 10-K\n\n## Important Caveat\n\nThe chunks provided **do not contain the detailed Property and Equipment breakdown table** by category (e.g., fulfillment equipment, technology infrastructure, construction-in-progress, other). That specific table — which typically appears in Note 1 (Description of Business, Accounting Policies, and Supplemental Disclosures) — is not included in the supplied text. What follows is everything the provided chunks *do* disclose about property and equipment and Project Kuiper (satellite network) assets.\n\n---\n\n## What the Chunks Do Disclose About Property and Equipment\n\n### 1. Geographic Split (U.S. vs. Non-U.S.)\n\nProperty and equipment, net **plus** operating leases, broken down geographically:\n\n| Region | Dec 31, 2023 | Dec 31, 2024 | Dec 31, 2025 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| U.S. | $196.0 billion | $241.6 billion | $321.9 billion |\n| Non-U.S. | $80.7 billion | $87.2 billion | $121.2 billion |\n\nOutside the U.S., no single country represented more than 10% of consolidated P&E, net and operating leases.\n\n### 2. Additions Under Finance Leases and Build-to-Suit Arrangements\n\nTwo footnotes (labeled (1) and (2) — likely corresponding to two P&E categories, presumably fulfillment-related and technology-infrastructure-related, though the category headers themselves are not in the provided chunks):\n\n**Footnote (1) — likely Fulfillment/Other:**\n- Finance lease additions: $525M (2023), $616M (2024), $1.0B (2025)\n- Build-to-suit additions: $356M (2023), $89M (2024), $20M (2025)\n\n**Footnote (2) — likely Technology Infrastructure:**\n- Finance lease additions: $117M (2023), $238M (2024), **$1.9B (2025)** — a sharp increase\n- Build-to-suit additions: $1M (2023), $8M (2024), **$421M (2025)** — also a sharp increase\n\nThe 2025 jump in footnote (2) is consistent with massive data center / AWS build-out.\n\n### 3. Segment Asset Allocation (Total Segment Assets, not P&E alone)\n\n| Segment | Dec 31, 2023 | Dec 31, 2024 | Dec 31, 2025 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| North America | $196,029M | $210,120M | $235,652M |\n| International | $69,718M | $69,487M | $81,984M |\n| AWS | $108,533M | $155,953M | **$252,588M** |\n| Corporate | $153,574M | $189,334M | $247,818M |\n| **Consolidated** | **$527,854M** | **$624,894M** | **$818,042M** |\n\nThe filing notes that **technology infrastructure assets** (included in P&E, net) are allocated to segments based on usage, with the **majority allocated to AWS** — which explains AWS\'s outsized asset growth in 2025 (from $156B to $253B).\n\n### 4. Facility Square Footage (Properties Section, as of Dec 31, 2025)\n\n| Description of Use | Leased (000s sq ft) | Owned (000s sq ft) | Location |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Office space | 31,028 | 9,160 | North America |\n| Office space | 26,495 | 1,802 | International |\n| Physical stores | 23,932 | 706 | North America |\n| Physical stores | 148 | — | International |\n| Fulfillment, data centers, and other | 474,128 | 45,803 | North America |\n| Fulfillment, data centers, and other | 185,814 | 20,660 | International |\n| **Total** | **741,545** | **78,131** | |\n\nBy segment (excluding corporate facilities):\n\n| Segment | Leased (000s sq ft) | Owned (000s sq ft) |\n|---|---|---|\n| North America | 481,153 | 25,437 |\n| International | 174,499 | 13,263 |\n| AWS | 28,370 | 28,469 |\n| **Total** | **684,022** | **67,169** |\n\nPhysical stores footnote: 615 North America and 8 International stores as of Dec 31, 2025.\n\n---\n\n## Project Kuiper / Satellite Network Disclosures\n\nThe filing discusses the satellite network (Project Kuiper) across several places, but **does not break out a separate satellite asset line on the balance sheet**. Instead, satellite-related costs are scattered across multiple balance sheet and income statement captions depending on their nature and stage:\n\n### Accounting Policy (Key Quote)\n> "We currently expense the majority of the costs associated with the development of our satellite network for global broadband service (including production, launch, and payroll costs, and launch services deposits upon launch). We will capitalize certain of these costs once the service achieves commercial viability, including sales to customers."\n\n### Where Satellite Costs Sit Today\n\n| Cost Type | Balance Sheet / Income Statement Location |\n|---|---|\n| **Launch services deposits (pre-launch)** | "Prepaid expenses and other current assets" — $6.9B total at Dec 31, 2025 (includes satellite deposits and non-income taxes; was $6.3B at Dec 31, 2024) |\n| **Launch services deposits (long-term portion)** | "Other assets" (long-term) — listed alongside convertible notes, equity investments, video/music content, deferred tax assets, intangibles, and affordable housing loans |\n| **Launch services deposits — upon launch** | Expensed immediately to "Technology and infrastructure" (income statement) |\n| **Production, launch, and payroll costs** | Expensed to "Technology and infrastructure" (income statement) until commercial viability |\n| **Future capitalization** | Once commercial viability (including sales to customers) is achieved, deposits will be reclassified to **Construction-in-Progress within "Property and equipment, net"** |\n\n### Reclassification Trigger\n> "We will reclassify the satellite network launch service deposits to construction-in-progress included within \'Property and equipment, net\' on our consolidated balance sheet once the service achieves commercial viability, including sales to customers."\n\n### Technology & Infrastructure Cost Context\nThe MD&A states that technology and infrastructure costs include "the development of a satellite network for global broadband service and autonomous vehicles for ride-hailing services." The 2025 increase in technology and infrastructure costs was "primarily due to an increase in spending on infrastructure, including depreciation and amortization," with FX increasing these costs by $312 million in 2025.\n\n### Purchase Obligations Related to Satellite\nThe unconditional purchase obligations footnote (Footnote 2 to the contractual obligations table) covers long-term agreements to "acquire and license digital media content, procure energy, acquire property and equipment, and license software." Satellite-specific purchase obligations are **not separately quantified** in the provided chunks. The footnote states that for agreements with variable terms, Amazon does "not estimate the total obligation beyond any minimum quantities and/or pricing, or termination penalties."\n\n---\n\n## What Is Missing From the Provided Chunks\n\nTo fully answer your question, the following items — which would normally appear in the 10-K but are **not in the supplied text** — would be needed:\n\n1. **The detailed P&E table** breaking out:\n   - Fulfillment and customer service equipment and property\n   - Technology infrastructure (servers, networking equipment, data centers)\n   - Construction-in-progress\n   - Other property and equipment\n   - Less: accumulated depreciation\n   - **Property and equipment, net**\n\n2. **A specific Project Kuiper purchase obligation or launch commitment figure** (if disclosed separately).\n\n3. **The full contractual obligations table** with line items and dollar amounts by period.\n\nIf you can provide the chunk containing Note 1\'s supplemental disclosures (the P&E table) or the full contractual obligations table, I can extract the category-level breakdown you\'re looking for.',
